5. Predation pressure index (PPI) to highlight value of genetics for informing natural mortality in fisheries management.

Followed similar approach as Richards and Jacobson (2016) using biomass/tow survey indices to weight percent frequency of occurrence of selected prey.

Shortfin had enough samples to look at PPI over area (SNE and MAB) and size (M, S), but I only considered area for Longfin at this stage since they were unevenly spread across SNE and MAB..

Results show that with the use of genetics in 2023, we uncovered higher predation pressure on most fishes (butterfish, silver hake, others) and this was ~ 1-2 orders of magnitude larger (2023 vs 1970s and 1980s). This was even true considering the unid. fish prey from the 1970s and 1980s. The increase was due to the genetic advantages of identifying prey, plus some increases in biomass/tow indices for these squids since the 1970s and 1980s.

To put this further into perspective, if you look at the total PPI of selected prey across groundfish with summer diet data from SNE and MAB, the added information from genetics shows we are ‘off’ by at least an order of magnitude in terms of predation pressure simply from these two squid alone.

Error bars represent 95% ci for PPI and were from simulated beta (FO) and gamma (biomass/tow) distributions based on mean and sd for FO and biomass indices.

6. Ways forward?

Molecular data only apply to fish prey, so focus more on FO less on biomass.

One use of these data could be a comparison of trad vs new/non trad methods to improve ecosystem knowledge/management. There is one upcoming AFS symposium on genomics which this work could connect.

Examine PPI (predator biomass weighted FO) to compare old data (1970s and 1980s) with new (2023) for various fish prey. Factors: decade (1970s, 1980s, 2023), size (S, M), geographic areas (MAB, SNE). Limit to fall for now until we get more data. Product would be PPI showing large difference between old vs new diet impact on prey fishes (butterfish, silver hake, sand lance, gsf) by squid and can also compare this PPI to PPI for other predators of these prey fishes.

Waiting for Fall 2023 BTS samples (~100) to be processed by genetics lab. Spring 2024 BTS squid currently being collected.
